   <sec>
    <title>
     β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     in the αɛθ–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     complex interacts with ɛ and the internal CBM in α
    </title>
    <p>
     Essentially identical ESI-MS results were obtained when αɛθ cores were assembled
     <em>
      in situ
     </em>
     from mixtures of separately dialysed subunits (middle panels in
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 4B
     </xref>
     and
     <a>
      Supplementary Figure S4A and B
     </a>
     , cf.
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 3C
     </xref>
     ), which enabled study of β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     binding to αɛθ cores with mutations in both α and ɛ.
     <em>
      E. coli
     </em>
     α contains two CBMs, but only the conserved internal motif is required for processive DNA synthesis (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Dohrmann and McHenry, 2005
     </xref>
     ). We used three variants of α to probe which of these sites binds β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     in the αɛθ–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     complex: α
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     , and the mutants αΔ7, which misses the last seven residues that comprise the C-terminal CBM (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      López de Saro et al, 2003a
     </xref>
     ), and one we term α
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     that has a strengthened internal CBM (QADMF changed to QLDLF;
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Dohrmann and McHenry, 2005
     </xref>
     ). ESI-MS of binding of these α variants to (excess) β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     showed clear evidence of an interaction with α
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     , but only weak binding to α
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     and αΔ7 (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 4A
     </xref>
     ). We then assembled αɛθ cores
     <em>
      in situ
     </em>
     with all combinations of α
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     , αΔ7, or α
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     with ɛ
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     , ɛ
     <sub>
      Q
     </sub>
     , or ɛ
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     , and mixed them with excess β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     . Regardless of which ɛ variant was used, ESI-MS showed that α
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     ɛθ and αΔ7ɛθ cores bound β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     with very similar efficiency, while α
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     ɛθ formed a much stronger complex (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 4B
     </xref>
     ;
     <a>
      Supplementary Figure S4
     </a>
     ). This clearly shows that only the internal CBM of α is required for formation of the αɛθ–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     complex detected by ESI-MS, and that β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     in this complex is sequestered by simultaneous interactions with two CBMs—a stronger one in α and a weaker one in ɛ.
    </p>
   </sec>
   <sec>
    <title>
     Role of ɛ–β interaction in strand extension by the Pol III core
    </title>
    <p>
     While the data clearly show (i) that ɛ contains a CBM in the intrinsically unstructured region immediately following its exonuclease domain (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 1A
     </xref>
     ) and (ii) that interaction of β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     at this site promotes SD synthesis by Pol III HE (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 2
     </xref>
     ), they do not yet establish if this interaction occurs during regular DNA synthesis. That ɛ increases the processivity of α in a β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     - and SSB-dependent synthesis reaction (
     <xref ref-type="bibr">
      Studwell and O'Donnell, 1990
     </xref>
     ) suggests this to be true, but this effect could be mediated solely through stabilization of α through its contacts with ɛ
     <sub>
      CTS
     </sub>
     .
    </p>
    <p>
     To further demonstrate the significance of ɛ–β interaction in the αɛθ–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     –DNA complex, we used an additional DNA synthesis assay, under ‘difficult' conditions. We found salt conditions (130 mM NaCl) where primer extension by Pol III core is strongly dependent on both β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     (
     <a>
      Supplementary Figure S5A
     </a>
     ) and the CBM of ɛ (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 5A
     </xref>
     ); proofreading activity is again not required (
     <a>
      Supplementary Figure S5B
     </a>
     ). In this assay, β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     is loaded onto primed ssDNA by the minimal γ
     <sub>
      3
     </sub>
     δδ′ clamp loader complex, thus disabling contacts between α and τ necessary for processivity. Moreover, SSB, required to melt secondary structures in the DNA, is omitted. Synthesis by the αɛ
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     θ core shows stalls (appearing as bands in the gel analysis) and it is slow, taking about 5 min before half of the template strands are fully replicated (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 5A
     </xref>
     , αɛ
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     θ core). Use of α alone or the αɛ
     <sub>
      Q
     </sub>
     θ core results in very little primer extension, while &gt;5-fold more extensive synthesis (fully replicated strands in &lt;2 min) is achieved by strengthening the CBM using ɛ
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 5A
     </xref>
     , αɛ
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     θ core). Consistent with the ESI-MS studies, this τ-independent strand-extension reaction involves simultaneous interactions of β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     with ɛ and the internal CBM in α, since αΔ7ɛ
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     θ is as active as wild-type αɛθ (
     <xref ref-type="fig">
      Figure 5B
     </xref>
     ); DNA synthesis is also stimulated by use of an α
     <sub>
      L
     </sub>
     ɛ
     <sub>
      wt
     </sub>
     θ core, with the strengthened internal CBM in α. These data indicate that in the absence of SSB, the α–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     complex is poorly processive and stalls readily on encounter with secondary structures in ssDNA, whereas the additional stabilization contributed by the ɛ–β interaction in the core–β
     <sub>
      2
     </sub>
     complex allows it to progress more efficiently.
    </p>
